# OverTheWire Bandit — Level 1

## Goal
Read a file called - (dash) stored in the 
home directory to find the password for Level 2

## Commands Used
ssh bandit1@bandit.labs.overthewire.org -p 2220
ls
cat ./-

## Solution
Logged into bandit1 using the password found 
in Level 0. Used ls to list files and found 
a file named - (a single dash).

Typing cat - did not work because Linux 
interprets - as "read from keyboard" not 
as a filename.

The fix was to use ./ before the filename 
which tells Linux to look in the current 
directory specifically:
cat ./-

This revealed the password for Level 2.

## What I Learned
- Files can be named with special characters
  like a dash which confuses normal commands
- Using ./ before a filename forces Linux to
  treat it as a file in the current directory
- cat - means read from keyboard in Linux
- Always use cat ./filename when filename
  starts with a special character